A child's immediate social and relational environment can affect their educational outcomes. Family income, education, and structure may affect a child's education, according to research. Low-income students are more likely to attend under-resourced schools, lack educational materials and technology, and have fewer extracurricular opportunities. Low-income students may struggle academically and graduate. Parental education affects a child's education. Educational resources and support are more likely for children of educated parents, which can improve educational outcomes. Family structure also affects education. Single-parent households are associated with lower academic achievement and graduation rates. Social capital—networks people's and resources—can also affect educational outcomes. Social capital—access to educational resources and networks—improves academic performance. In conclusion, a child's immediate social and relational environment can affect their educational outcomes. Family income, parental education, family structure, and social capital can affect a child's education. 